1
00:01:51,720 --> 00:01:53,517
Morning.

2
00:01:55,440 --> 00:01:57,237
it is a commonplace observation

3
00:01:57,320 --> 00:02:01,029
that remarkable events
often have ordinary beginnings.

4
00:02:02,440 --> 00:02:06,399
Never was this more true
than of my talks with Dean Spanley,

5
00:02:06,480 --> 00:02:08,789
which form the spine of our narrative.

6
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:10,677
- Morning.
- Morning.

7
00:02:10,760 --> 00:02:13,513
Properly speaking,
they began on a Thursday,

8
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:18,913
the day on which i visit my father,
Mr Horatio Fisk.

9
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,913
This habit - one might even say ritual -

10
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,278
commenced after the death of my younger
brother Harrington in the Boer War

11
00:02:28,280 --> 00:02:30,669
and the subsequent demise
of my dear mama,

12
00:02:30,760 --> 00:02:35,550
occasioned by her grief
at this unsupportable loss.

13
00:02:49,640 --> 00:02:52,598
I'm coming, I'm coming.

14
00:02:55,200 --> 00:02:58,033
Morning, Mrs Brimley.

15
00:02:58,120 --> 00:03:00,315
- How are you today?.
- As you see me.

16
00:03:00,400 --> 00:03:02,516
Could complain,
but what'd be the use of that?.

17
00:03:02,600 --> 00:03:04,511
Yes, indeed.

18
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:12,797
And himself?.

19
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:16,350
Oh, he's working himself up
into a head of steam.

20
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:18,590
You know how he gets.

21
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:22,990
Sent back the paper, he did,
to have it properly ironed.

22
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:27,797
I'm just finishing the obituaries,
so you can take it in to him.

23
00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:30,394
I thought he didn't read the obituaries.

24
00:03:30,480 --> 00:03:35,474
No more he does, but he wants them
ironed just the same.

25
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:37,312
Says he doesn't read them

26
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:42,076
because he's afraid he'II come across
his own name one day. I ask you!

27
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,788
Do you believe in the transmigration
of souls, Mrs Brimley?.

28
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:06,714
I don't believe in Ietting foreigners in,
if that's what you mean.

29
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:12,158
No, um... reincarnation,
not immigration.

30
00:04:12,240 --> 00:04:17,837
Um, the belief that the immortal soul
has many earthly homes.

31
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:22,269
Well, I haven't given it much thought,
I haven't.

32
00:04:24,680 --> 00:04:29,356
After AIbert died
I went to one of them mediums,

33
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:32,231
but she couldn't get hold of him.

34
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:35,118
I wasn't surprised, mind you.
He never said much when he were alive.

35
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:37,919
I couldn't imagine him piping up
once he were dead.

36
00:04:39,520 --> 00:04:42,273
Mind you don't crease that, now.

37
00:04:43,840 --> 00:04:47,435
He won't know what day it is,
not having seen the paper.

38
00:05:38,160 --> 00:05:42,711
- Oh, young Fisk. It must be Thursday.
- It is indeed.

39
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:47,715
Very handy, a Thursday. Keeps
Wednesday and Friday from colliding.

40
00:05:47,800 --> 00:05:49,791
You're here, then.

41
00:06:00,720 --> 00:06:02,995
You should have
the garden seen to, Father.

42
00:06:03,080 --> 00:06:06,197
- That was your mother's job.
- Nevertheless...

43
00:06:06,280 --> 00:06:09,795
Nevertheless. What does
that expression mean, I ask you?.

44
00:06:09,880 --> 00:06:12,235
Nevertheless.

45
00:06:12,320 --> 00:06:15,915
Might as well be clearing your throat,
for all the sense it makes.

46
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:23,310
Well, it's a fine day, Father.
Have you anything particular in mind?.

47
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:25,391
I can see how fine the day is.

48
00:06:25,480 --> 00:06:29,439
As for particular in mind, everything
is particular when you get down to it.

49
00:06:29,520 --> 00:06:32,273
What I meant was, do you have any plans?.

50
00:06:32,360 --> 00:06:39,869
Are there any concerts or exhibitions,
diversions you wish to attend?.

51
00:06:39,960 --> 00:06:42,030
There's nothing about the war.

52
00:06:42,120 --> 00:06:44,270
We're not presently at war,
as far as I know.

53
00:06:44,360 --> 00:06:46,157
Diversions, you say.

54
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:48,231
That's all that's Ieft, you know,

55
00:06:48,320 --> 00:06:51,232
before stepping
out of the anteroom of eternity.

56
00:06:53,440 --> 00:06:57,797
There is a display of aboriginal weapons
from our wars of imperial conquest...

57
00:06:57,880 --> 00:07:01,236
Such was the common procedure
of my relationship with my father.

58
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:07,031
i, carrying out my filial duty,
would arrive with the best of intentions.

59
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:11,989
He, indulging his practised
yet primitive paternal instincts,

60
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:14,036
would play a strange game of control.

61
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:18,240
As Thursday upon Thursday arrived,

62
00:07:18,320 --> 00:07:23,394
i'd become more and more determined
to see this game dismantled.

63
00:07:23,480 --> 00:07:28,156
A collection of Georgian shoe buckles.
Over 2, 000 items.

64
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:33,360
That was an era when a gentleman could
spend a fortune ornamenting his feet.

65
00:07:35,600 --> 00:07:37,636
Did we win the Boer War?.

66
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:42,433
I believe we Iost more slowly
than the other side.

67
00:07:42,520 --> 00:07:44,795
Garden never recovered from it.

68
00:07:48,560 --> 00:07:53,031
You know, there is a Iecture
by one Swami Nala Prash

69
00:07:53,120 --> 00:07:55,350
on the transmigration of souls.

70
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:57,510
Poppycock!

71
00:07:57,600 --> 00:08:01,593
Think if we had souls they wouldn't
get in touch?. Of course they would.

72
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:04,035
Think your mother wouldn't be on to me
about that garden?. Of course she would.

73
00:08:05,560 --> 00:08:08,757
Still, it seems the most Iikely
of the Iot, wouldn't you say?.

74
00:08:08,840 --> 00:08:12,230
It's being held at the home
of the Nawab of Ranjiput.

75
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:15,835
- Isn't that the cricketing Indian chappie?.
- Yes, I believe so.

76
00:08:15,920 --> 00:08:18,036
Oh, well. Let's take a Iook.

77
00:08:18,120 --> 00:08:20,714
Heard tell he's turned the ballroom
into a cricket pitch.

78
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:23,189
Mad as badgers, these nawabs.

79
00:08:23,280 --> 00:08:27,512
Oh, by the way,
I've invested in a chair vehicle.

80
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:30,558
Makes walking unnecessary.
You'II enjoy it.

81
00:08:30,640 --> 00:08:33,632
Mrs Brimley! My chair!

82
00:08:36,800 --> 00:08:40,236
- Watch your step, young Fisk.
- Thank you, Father.

83
00:08:43,320 --> 00:08:46,551
- How is it going?.
- Very smoothly so far.

84
00:08:46,640 --> 00:08:49,518
So it should. Latest model.

85
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:52,433
Guaranteed to Iast Ionger than the user.

86
00:08:52,520 --> 00:08:56,308
- Not that that means very much.
- Nonsense, Father.

88
00:09:06,600 --> 00:09:08,989
Damned machines!

89
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:12,514
Be the death of all of us, they will.

90
00:09:12,600 --> 00:09:16,115
Progress, Father,
occasions certain inconveniences.

91
00:09:18,160 --> 00:09:22,312
- Galsworthy, old son. How are you?.
- Very well, sir.

92
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:27,952
Hey-ho! Well done, chair.

93
00:09:29,240 --> 00:09:31,276
Give you a hand with the buggy?.

94
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:33,510
- Grab hold.
- That's kind of you.

95
00:09:33,600 --> 00:09:36,114
- Buggy, indeed!
- My pleasure, sir.

96
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:38,430
CIyde-built by the feel of it.

99
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:02,431
AIways a pleasure.

100
00:10:02,520 --> 00:10:04,636
Thank you. Thank you.

101
00:10:05,720 --> 00:10:10,430
Damn foolish game, cricket,
if you ask me. Too many rules.

102
00:10:12,200 --> 00:10:15,192
- Howzat!
- Not out, I say.

103
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:28,192
- Not exactly a full house, is it?.
- This is where you need to go.

104
00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:32,237
Want to be where we can see
the yellow of his eyes.

105
00:10:33,880 --> 00:10:37,714
I declare, that's Spanley,
dean of St Justus.

106
00:10:37,800 --> 00:10:40,917
Not that I ever go there,
so he may have been kicked out by now.

107
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:42,911
- Father, keep your voice down.
- What?.

108
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:44,433
Shh.

109
00:10:46,040 --> 00:10:48,031
Dean Spanley, did you say?.

110
00:10:48,120 --> 00:10:50,429
Not me. Chap with the dog collar.

111
00:10:50,520 --> 00:10:54,069
What's a dean doing
at a sermon on reincarnation?.

112
00:10:54,160 --> 00:10:57,596
- Exactly my thought.
- I think it shows open-mindedness.

113
00:10:57,680 --> 00:11:01,355
Impending apostasy, more Iike.
Seen the error of his Christian ways.

114
00:11:01,440 --> 00:11:04,273
- The name's Wrather, with a W.
- Fisk.

115
00:11:04,360 --> 00:11:07,636
- What brings you here, Mr Fisk?.
- Ask young Fisk. His idea.

116
00:11:07,720 --> 00:11:09,517
The Iesser of several evils.

118
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:17,351
Well, there you are.

119
00:11:17,440 --> 00:11:19,431
I thought I got a thin edge onto my pad,

120
00:11:19,520 --> 00:11:22,717
but when the umpire raises his finger,
you have to walk.

121
00:11:22,800 --> 00:11:25,314
That's Iife... and cricket.

122
00:11:26,360 --> 00:11:28,828
Well, then,
time to bring on Swami Prash.

123
00:11:28,920 --> 00:11:31,514
Of what he will tell you
I have no particular opinion,

124
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:34,990
but I've always held him in high regard
as a cricketer.

125
00:11:35,080 --> 00:11:38,038
Bowled decent Ieft-arm Ieg breaks
before he went holy.

126
00:11:38,120 --> 00:11:42,955
Haven't seen him play since, but I've no doubt
he's still the sportsman he was. Hm.

127
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:55,397
i confess, the appearance of Swami Prash
came as something of a surprise,

128
00:11:55,480 --> 00:11:57,869
even a disappointment.

129
00:11:57,960 --> 00:12:01,873
For although i had no clear expectation
of what a holy man would look like,

130
00:12:01,960 --> 00:12:05,396
i had imagined one with such a title
and discussing such a subject

131
00:12:05,480 --> 00:12:08,711
to have been dressed more...
traditionally.

132
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:25,511
The question of
the transmigration of the soul,

133
00:12:25,600 --> 00:12:31,436
perhaps more familiarly known to you
as reincarnation,

134
00:12:31,520 --> 00:12:34,830
has been the structural underpinning

135
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:40,472
of Indian philosophical
and religious thought for millennia.

136
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:42,039
Only recently...

137
00:12:42,120 --> 00:12:45,271
What ensued proved to be
as unilluminating a 50 minutes

138
00:12:45,360 --> 00:12:50,309
as i can remember spending outside
the confines of parliamentary debate.

139
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:53,039
.. esoteric wisdom
come to the attention...

140
00:12:53,120 --> 00:12:57,557
indeed, the most significant fact
i gleaned from the experience

141
00:12:57,640 --> 00:13:04,239
was that with my eyes closed,
the lecturer could have been a Welshman.

142
00:13:04,320 --> 00:13:08,677
A Iittle, if only a Iittle, closer.

144
00:13:11,960 --> 00:13:15,839
I should be pleased now
to answer any questions you may have.

145
00:13:15,920 --> 00:13:18,992
- Where am I?.
- Be quiet.

146
00:13:19,080 --> 00:13:21,753
You are, my dear sir,

147
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:26,755
in the anteroom of eternity
with the rest of us sojourning souls.

148
00:13:26,840 --> 00:13:29,035
- What?.
- Yes, madam?.

149
00:13:29,120 --> 00:13:35,514
I was, er... we were, that is,
wondering if...

150
00:13:35,600 --> 00:13:38,797
- Did he say the anteroom of eternity?.
- Shh.

151
00:13:38,880 --> 00:13:41,394
- What?.
- Shh.

152
00:13:41,480 --> 00:13:46,395
- If they...
- Pets, really. The souls of pets.

153
00:13:46,480 --> 00:13:52,794
That is a most interesting question
and I thank you for asking it.

155
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:58,753
It is generally supposed
that the animal soul

156
00:13:58,840 --> 00:14:01,832
must be of a different
and, by inference,

157
00:14:01,920 --> 00:14:05,515
inferior nature to the human soul.

158
00:14:05,600 --> 00:14:11,118
The soul is that part of the Godhead,
of AII That Is...

159
00:14:11,200 --> 00:14:15,239
What you said before, sir,
about the anteroom of eternity...

160
00:14:15,320 --> 00:14:18,596
Would you be kind enough to allow
the swami to finish his thought, sir?.

161
00:14:18,680 --> 00:14:19,908
- Well, well.
- Shh.

162
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:21,991
- What?.
- Shh.

163
00:14:26,520 --> 00:14:33,119
However, although all animals have
their specific awareness of the Godhead,

164
00:14:33,400 --> 00:14:41,910
the dog is, by virtue of his singular
relationship with all mankind, unique.

165
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:44,355
What about cats?.

166
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:48,399
The dog amplifies...

167
00:14:48,480 --> 00:14:51,074
the cat diminishes...

168
00:14:52,080 --> 00:14:55,231
man's estimation of himself.

169
00:14:56,320 --> 00:14:58,197
Poppycock!

171
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,594
So I shall wish you gentlemen good day.

172
00:15:04,680 --> 00:15:08,559
I can be found here most mornings
and of the occasional evening.

173
00:15:08,640 --> 00:15:11,393
What exactly is a conveyancer?.

174
00:15:11,800 --> 00:15:14,030
Well, nothing, exactly.
More a service of facilitation.

175
00:15:14,120 --> 00:15:16,429
Assisting a thing
to be moved between parties.

176
00:15:16,520 --> 00:15:18,750
So you're a middleman.

177
00:15:18,840 --> 00:15:21,593
Well, sometimes in the middle
and sometimes at either end.

178
00:15:21,680 --> 00:15:25,753
- Been a great pleasure, sir.
- You're easily pleased, is all I can say.

179
00:15:30,480 --> 00:15:35,508
Mrs Travers, did I ever tell you that
I collect birds?. I'm a real cornucopian.

180
00:15:35,600 --> 00:15:37,511
What's that?.

181
00:15:42,400 --> 00:15:45,073
Only thing that made sense
in the whole damn farrago

182
00:15:45,160 --> 00:15:48,470
was what the chap said about dogs
thinking you are better than you are.

183
00:15:48,560 --> 00:15:51,518
Canine flattery is a survival mechanism,
according to Darwin.

184
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:54,034
The chap never had a dog,
is all I can say.

185
00:15:54,120 --> 00:15:56,076
I thought he had a beagle.

186
00:15:56,160 --> 00:16:01,109
I had a dog once. Wag.
One of the seven great dogs.

187
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:04,749
At any one time, you know,
there are only seven. Did you know that?.

188
00:16:04,840 --> 00:16:06,910
I can't say I did.

189
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:10,834
Neither did that swami. Made me think
he didn't know much about dogs.

190
00:16:10,920 --> 00:16:14,071
Let's go to my club, have a stiff one.

191
00:16:14,160 --> 00:16:16,310
I thought you didn't go there any more.

192
00:16:16,400 --> 00:16:19,836
That was in the past.
This is the present, young Fisk.

193
00:16:19,920 --> 00:16:22,798
There's no time Iike the present,
as that swami called it.

194
00:16:22,880 --> 00:16:27,908
- What was it?. The Eternal Now?.
- I don't know, sir. I wasn't Iistening.

196
00:16:38,680 --> 00:16:42,229
- How are you, Marriot?.
- I'm well, sir. And yourself?.

197
00:16:42,320 --> 00:16:45,153
Oh, one step nearer the grave.

198
00:16:45,240 --> 00:16:47,834
How's that boy of yours?.
Tommy, isn't it?.

199
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:51,514
Yes, sir. Tommy, sir.

200
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:54,711
He... he's dead, sir.

201
00:16:55,720 --> 00:16:58,154
The war, sir. The Boer War.

202
00:16:58,240 --> 00:17:02,631
Oh, the Boers.
Lost one myself in that nonsense.

203
00:17:05,360 --> 00:17:08,352
Haven't seen you for a while, sir.

204
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:16,191
Hasn't changed much.

205
00:17:16,280 --> 00:17:19,875
CIubs aren't supposed to change, surely.
Part of their charm.

206
00:17:23,840 --> 00:17:26,308
There's that chap again.
Is he following us?.

207
00:17:26,400 --> 00:17:28,675
Where are you going?.

208
00:17:33,160 --> 00:17:34,957
- Fisk.
- What?.

209
00:17:35,040 --> 00:17:37,395
Horatio Fisk.

210
00:17:37,480 --> 00:17:41,632
This is young Fisk. Surprised
we were to see you at the nawab's.

211
00:17:41,720 --> 00:17:43,711
Oh, yes, yes.

212
00:17:43,800 --> 00:17:48,078
So, what did you make
of all that mumble-jumble?.

214
00:17:50,720 --> 00:17:52,870
The beliefs of others
are always of interest.

215
00:17:52,960 --> 00:17:58,318
Really?. Tell me this, then.
Why don't they get in touch?.

216
00:18:00,240 --> 00:18:04,518
Souls, I mean.
Never a word from beyond the grave.

217
00:18:04,600 --> 00:18:07,353
You'd think one of them
would have given a shout.

218
00:18:07,440 --> 00:18:10,159
Well, I imagine if the swami is correct

219
00:18:10,240 --> 00:18:13,630
they're all too busy
being whoever they've become.

220
00:18:13,720 --> 00:18:16,109
And what about him pinching my Iine?.

221
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:19,033
- What Iine was that?.
- The anteroom of eternity.

222
00:18:19,120 --> 00:18:21,429
Well, I'd rather thought that
common usage.

223
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:25,069
Not at all.
Out of my own head that came.

224
00:18:25,160 --> 00:18:27,230
Rather Iike having your pocket picked.

225
00:18:27,320 --> 00:18:31,711
- What's that you're drinking?.
- Ah, this is Tokay.

226
00:18:31,800 --> 00:18:36,635
Not an Imperial, I'm afraid,
but... good enough, for all that.

227
00:18:37,640 --> 00:18:39,596
A bit syrupy for my taste.

228
00:18:41,280 --> 00:18:43,316
Well, we'II Ieave you to it.

229
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:50,238
You must excuse my father.
He can be... rather impulsive.

230
00:18:50,320 --> 00:18:52,356
Not at all.

231
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:57,958
Pardon me, Dean, but...

232
00:18:58,040 --> 00:19:02,158
am I to understand you give
some credence to these beliefs?.

233
00:19:04,120 --> 00:19:09,148
- Only the closed mind is certain, sir.
- Oh, I agree.

234
00:19:10,880 --> 00:19:12,871
I agree.

235
00:19:12,960 --> 00:19:15,713
- Good day, sir.
- Good day to you, sir.

236
00:19:29,840 --> 00:19:31,990
Rum chap, Spanley.

237
00:19:32,080 --> 00:19:34,878
Do you know him well enough
to form that opinion?.

238
00:19:34,960 --> 00:19:37,190
One can tell. Not quite sound.

239
00:19:37,280 --> 00:19:40,909
Dabbling in Eastern religion.
Drinking that Hungarian treacle.

240
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:44,117
Can I get you gentlemen a drink?.

241
00:19:45,400 --> 00:19:49,678
I'd Iike a brandy and soda, Marriot,
with the emphasis on the brandy.

242
00:19:49,760 --> 00:19:51,955
I'II have the Tokay.

243
00:19:52,040 --> 00:19:57,433
Oh, I'm afraid that won't be possible, sir.
The Tokay's private stock.

244
00:19:57,520 --> 00:19:59,795
The dean keeps a bottle
for his personal use.

245
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:02,633
Very hard to come by, I believe.

246
00:20:02,720 --> 00:20:06,429
Damned unsociable of him.
Told you the fellow wasn't sound.

247
00:20:07,760 --> 00:20:13,392
In that case I'II have a brandy and soda
as well. In the inverse ratio.

248
00:20:13,480 --> 00:20:15,516
Yes, of course, sir.

249
00:20:17,760 --> 00:20:21,958
If I... may say so, Mr Fisk,

250
00:20:23,400 --> 00:20:25,994
I'm most sorry to hear of your Ioss.

251
00:20:26,080 --> 00:20:30,710
- What?.
- Did you... Your boy, sir. In the war.

252
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:36,355
Wasn't my Ioss. He's the one got killed.

253
00:20:40,040 --> 00:20:41,439
Sir.

254
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:46,510
That was, even for you, Father,
a singularly callous remark.

255
00:20:46,600 --> 00:20:48,591
Nothing of the sort.

256
00:20:48,680 --> 00:20:52,195
Here we sit about to be served
brandy and sodas.

257
00:20:52,280 --> 00:20:55,795
What's our Ioss
compared to your brother's?.

258
00:20:59,080 --> 00:21:04,279
Women with the vote is Iike a cow
with a gun - contrary to nature.

259
00:21:05,040 --> 00:21:07,793
Walking home, listening to my father

260
00:21:07,880 --> 00:21:11,998
assert a variety of things
in tones of unbrookable authority,

261
00:21:12,080 --> 00:21:16,232
Dean Spanley's words returned to me
with renewed force".

262
00:21:17,560 --> 00:21:20,438
"Only the closed mind is certain. "

263
00:21:25,440 --> 00:21:28,159
An excellent hotpot, M rs Brimley.

264
00:21:28,240 --> 00:21:29,798
Well, it ought to be,

265
00:21:29,880 --> 00:21:33,873
seeing as how I've made it for you
about five hundred times.

266
00:21:34,760 --> 00:21:36,318
Thank you.

267
00:21:40,120 --> 00:21:42,475
"It may well be supposed
that this turn of events

268
00:21:42,560 --> 00:21:45,313
came as a most disagreeable surprise
to Mr Chuttleworth,

269
00:21:45,400 --> 00:21:49,552
accustomed as he was
to having his every whim catered for."

270
00:21:49,640 --> 00:21:53,235
i confess i had, until that moment,

271
00:21:53,320 --> 00:21:55,709
always supposed certainty
to be rather a good thing.

272
00:21:56,720 --> 00:21:58,756
Like money in the bank.

273
00:21:58,840 --> 00:22:04,073
But something in the day's events
had occasioned in me a certain disquiet,

274
00:22:04,160 --> 00:22:06,071
a sense that...

275
00:22:06,160 --> 00:22:08,913
There may be more things
in heaven and earth, Horatio,

276
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:11,195
than are dreamt of in your philosophy.

279
00:23:50,600 --> 00:23:52,591
I'II be off, Mrs Brimley.

280
00:23:52,680 --> 00:23:54,830
He's dozing in the study.

281
00:23:54,920 --> 00:23:58,799
Oh, I'II have to wake him up,
otherwise he won't sleep tonight.

282
00:24:06,280 --> 00:24:08,316
Does he ever mention my brother?.

283
00:24:10,320 --> 00:24:15,440
Your father doesn't hold with grieving,
Mr Fisk, as you well know.

284
00:24:15,520 --> 00:24:17,954
No, that's right.

285
00:24:20,200 --> 00:24:21,792
No, you're right.

286
00:24:23,800 --> 00:24:25,791
Thank you, Mrs Brimley.

287
00:24:27,120 --> 00:24:30,829
- And thank you for the hotpot.
- Oh, don't you start, young man.

288
00:24:30,920 --> 00:24:33,388
Hotpot, that's all
he'II Iet me cook for him.

289
00:24:33,480 --> 00:24:37,268
Creature of habit, your father is. Knows
what he wants without having to think.

290
00:24:37,360 --> 00:24:39,828
The certainty of a closed mind.

291
00:24:39,920 --> 00:24:45,358
Well, I don't know about that.
But you do know where you are with him.

292
00:24:45,440 --> 00:24:48,989
Where you was before. Nowhere.

293
00:24:50,160 --> 00:24:54,472
- Bye-bye. I'II see you next Thursday.
- Like as not.

294
00:24:57,040 --> 00:24:59,395
Creatures of habit. Oh!

295
00:25:06,400 --> 00:25:09,631
i've heard it said
that one encounter is a happenstance,

296
00:25:09,720 --> 00:25:15,352
two a coincidence
and three a significance.

297
00:25:16,840 --> 00:25:18,831
Be that as it may,

298
00:25:18,920 --> 00:25:24,597
that day i found myself, for the third
time, in the presence of Dean Spanley,

299
00:25:24,680 --> 00:25:29,913
a man who, until that day,
i did not know existed.

301
00:25:32,120 --> 00:25:34,111
Is it stuck up there?.

302
00:25:34,200 --> 00:25:38,796
It rather appears so.
They never think of that when they go up,

303
00:25:38,880 --> 00:25:41,872
which I consider a serious reflection
on their intelligence.

304
00:25:41,960 --> 00:25:43,951
Probably chased by a dog.

305
00:25:45,800 --> 00:25:48,633
Dean?. Dean Spanley?.

306
00:25:48,720 --> 00:25:53,077
Hello. I met you earlier at your club.

307
00:25:53,160 --> 00:25:56,869
I was introduced by my father. Mr Fisk.

308
00:25:56,960 --> 00:25:58,552
Oh.

309
00:25:58,640 --> 00:26:02,076
- And you were at the nawab's.
- Ah, yes.

310
00:26:04,120 --> 00:26:08,591
I am most eager to hear your further
views on the subject of reincarnation.

311
00:26:08,680 --> 00:26:11,831
I assure you, sir, I have
no special knowledge on the matter.

312
00:26:11,920 --> 00:26:14,992
Compared to my own,
I'm sure yours are encyclopaedic.

313
00:26:15,080 --> 00:26:18,117
I was wondering if I might invite you
to dinner one evening.

314
00:26:18,200 --> 00:26:22,193
I'm afraid that with my schedule
that would be rather difficult.

315
00:26:22,280 --> 00:26:25,431
I would not presume
upon so short an acquaintance

316
00:26:25,520 --> 00:26:28,956
were it not that I've recently come
into possession of a bottle of Tokay.

317
00:26:29,040 --> 00:26:31,031
An Imperial Tokay.

318
00:26:32,760 --> 00:26:36,355
- An Imperial Tokay?.
- Yes.

319
00:26:39,320 --> 00:26:44,394
One must be on one's guard against
the common or garden variety. What year?.

320
00:26:45,800 --> 00:26:49,588
- An '89, I believe.
- An '89, you say?.

321
00:26:50,720 --> 00:26:53,598
Was... is that a good year?.

322
00:26:53,680 --> 00:26:58,754
Oh, yes. How do you come to be
in possession of such a treasure?.

323
00:26:58,840 --> 00:27:02,071
You must be very well connected, Mr...

324
00:27:02,160 --> 00:27:05,516
Fisk. Henslowe Fisk.

325
00:27:07,400 --> 00:27:09,391
Well... Well...

326
00:27:09,480 --> 00:27:11,675
Perhaps I might manage... Thursday,
if that would be convenient?.

327
00:27:16,520 --> 00:27:18,670
Most convenient.

328
00:27:18,760 --> 00:27:20,910
Shall we say seven o'clock?.

329
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:24,959
- Very well. Until then.
- Good day, sir.

330
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:29,717
'89. Goodness me.

332
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:35,117
I wouldn't call it a Iie, puss.

333
00:27:36,880 --> 00:27:41,192
More Iike a truth deferred.
Nothing worse.

334
00:27:46,520 --> 00:27:49,398
it had not occurred to me
when i made my overture to the dean

335
00:27:49,480 --> 00:27:53,155
that procuring his favourite tipple
would prove such a challenge.

336
00:27:53,240 --> 00:27:55,231
Oi! Come back here!

338
00:28:04,680 --> 00:28:07,433
Very hard to find
an Imperial Tokay, sir.

339
00:28:07,520 --> 00:28:10,398
Of course there are what you might call
commercial counterfeits.

340
00:28:10,480 --> 00:28:12,994
But the real thing,
that's another story altogether.

341
00:28:13,080 --> 00:28:15,799
It's made solely
for the Hapsburg monarchy, you see.

342
00:28:15,880 --> 00:28:18,838
Takes a royal decree
to have one uncorked.

343
00:28:19,720 --> 00:28:22,678
You would need to know
somebody with such connections.

344
00:28:22,760 --> 00:28:24,751
I see.

345
00:28:26,440 --> 00:28:31,878
Tell me this. If King Edward himself
were to come you and say".

346
00:28:33,840 --> 00:28:36,991
"Find me one or two bottles of Tokay",
what would you say to him?.

347
00:28:37,080 --> 00:28:39,833
Well, I would suggest,
most respectfully,

348
00:28:39,920 --> 00:28:44,038
that he uses his family connections
in order to affect the conveyancing.

349
00:28:44,120 --> 00:28:48,238
So he'd have a Iot more chance
of success than I would, sir.

350
00:28:49,800 --> 00:28:51,756
Of course.

351
00:29:09,120 --> 00:29:12,715
The point of the exercise,
drop every ball without a miss.

352
00:29:14,960 --> 00:29:17,474
Care for a small wager?.

353
00:29:17,560 --> 00:29:22,315
No, thank you. No, you seem more
than capable of performing such a feat.

354
00:29:25,800 --> 00:29:30,032
So you'd Iike to acquire
a bottle of an '89 Tokay.

355
00:29:30,120 --> 00:29:32,076
An Imperial.

356
00:29:32,160 --> 00:29:34,720
This an adventure of the romantic sort
that you're embarking on?.

357
00:29:34,800 --> 00:29:36,836
Certainly not.

358
00:29:38,160 --> 00:29:41,197
It is said that the fair sex
responds avidly to Tokay.

359
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:44,989
Loosens the morals
and with it the corsets.

360
00:29:45,920 --> 00:29:50,152
- How high are you willing to go?.
- Whatever it costs.

361
00:29:50,240 --> 00:29:51,639
Within reason.

362
00:29:51,720 --> 00:29:54,280
Ah, yes. Well, you see,
there's the rub, within reason.

363
00:29:54,360 --> 00:29:58,069
- '89 Tokay not easy to come by.
- So I understand.

364
00:29:59,760 --> 00:30:01,751
So what's your Iine, then?.

365
00:30:01,840 --> 00:30:04,912
Oh, this and that.
A bit of art publishing.

366
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:06,752
Any money in it?.

367
00:30:06,840 --> 00:30:10,515
A modest remuneration.
But the real reward is in the art itself.

368
00:30:10,600 --> 00:30:15,628
Though I must admit there must be
rather more to be made in conveyancing.

369
00:30:15,720 --> 00:30:19,713
It's not all mine.
I'm just a ground-floor tenant.

370
00:30:24,400 --> 00:30:26,834
How on earth
did you come by all this stuff?.

371
00:30:26,920 --> 00:30:30,754
My Auntie Molly was a hoarder.
Caught it from her, I shouldn't wonder.

372
00:30:30,840 --> 00:30:32,671
What do you do with it?.

373
00:30:32,760 --> 00:30:35,149
Oh, you never know when someone wants
something you just happen to have.

374
00:30:37,440 --> 00:30:40,238
Such as a bottle of Imperial Tokay.

375
00:30:40,320 --> 00:30:42,311
Really?.

376
00:30:44,640 --> 00:30:46,198
Good grief.

377
00:30:46,280 --> 00:30:49,909
It's not an '89, I'm afraid.
Will a '91 do?.

378
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:51,911
It'II have to.

379
00:30:53,520 --> 00:30:58,674
I suppose I could say I was promised
an '89 and the man was mistaken.

380
00:31:00,160 --> 00:31:02,151
What do you think?.

381
00:31:03,280 --> 00:31:05,840
- How much is this?.
- Five guineas to you.

382
00:31:05,920 --> 00:31:09,913
Five guineas?.
That's a bit bloody steep.

383
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:13,709
These Iittle things were sent to try us,
as the man said of the pygmy judge.

384
00:31:18,160 --> 00:31:20,276
Thursday?.

385
00:31:20,360 --> 00:31:23,352
Are there not
six other perfectly adequate days,

386
00:31:23,440 --> 00:31:26,830
each equipped with portions of time
suitable for such activities?.

387
00:31:26,920 --> 00:31:29,309
Thursday is the only day
the dean is free.

388
00:31:29,400 --> 00:31:31,868
Poppycock.
Deans have dinner every evening.

389
00:31:31,960 --> 00:31:33,313
He has prior engagements.

390
00:31:33,400 --> 00:31:36,437
Is my Thursday not a prior engagement,
young Fisk?.

391
00:31:41,360 --> 00:31:43,794
What is going on?.

392
00:31:44,920 --> 00:31:47,639
You're not getting married, I hope.

393
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:52,195
- No.
- Good.

394
00:31:55,880 --> 00:31:58,314
If I had it to do over again...

395
00:31:58,400 --> 00:32:03,030
Am I to understand from that remark
that you regret marrying Mother?.

396
00:32:04,280 --> 00:32:06,396
Fine woman, AIice.

397
00:32:08,680 --> 00:32:10,671
Very good in the garden.

398
00:32:14,120 --> 00:32:17,237
No, it's the children.

399
00:32:17,320 --> 00:32:20,756
Hostages to fortune is what they are.

400
00:32:20,840 --> 00:32:24,037
But there is no point
to regretting things

401
00:32:24,120 --> 00:32:26,759
that have gone to the trouble
of happening.

402
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:31,993
And that is your reason
for refusing to mourn Harrington?.

403
00:32:32,080 --> 00:32:35,868
I warned your brother
that the war would be bad for his health,

404
00:32:35,960 --> 00:32:37,916
but no, he knew better, the young fool.

405
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:40,798
Anyway, your mother mourned him
enough for both of us.

406
00:32:40,880 --> 00:32:42,836
Perhaps if you'd shared
that burden with her

407
00:32:42,920 --> 00:32:45,195
she might not have found her grief
so insupportable.

408
00:32:51,360 --> 00:32:55,148
I have nothing more to say
on this subject.

409
00:32:55,240 --> 00:32:57,959
PIease never mention it to me again.

410
00:32:58,040 --> 00:33:00,270
CIose the door on your way out.

411
00:33:11,200 --> 00:33:15,796
- Do you miss your husband, Mrs Brimley?.
- Miss him?.

412
00:33:17,160 --> 00:33:21,153
Oh, well. He weren't hard to miss,
were AIbert.

413
00:33:21,240 --> 00:33:24,789
Kept himself to himself.

414
00:33:24,880 --> 00:33:28,759
Sat in that chair night after night,
never said a word.

415
00:33:28,840 --> 00:33:33,675
Just nodded, sociable-Iike,
and spat in the fire every now and again.

416
00:33:33,760 --> 00:33:36,638
That were AIbert's one bad habit.

417
00:33:39,680 --> 00:33:43,559
I talk to the chair sometimes
and it's just Iike old times.

418
00:33:43,640 --> 00:33:45,756
Except the chair don't spit.

419
00:33:56,280 --> 00:33:58,840
Thinking about your brother
and your mum, are you?.

420
00:34:01,560 --> 00:34:04,120
I just wish Father would...

421
00:34:07,200 --> 00:34:10,510
Well, Mr Fisk was never one
for showing much.

422
00:34:13,440 --> 00:34:15,749
Why, I remember that night
up at the Iake

423
00:34:15,840 --> 00:34:19,230
when you and young Harry went out
on that cockleshell of a boat.

424
00:34:24,320 --> 00:34:29,235
Yes. Wasn't one of his finest moments.

425
00:34:32,760 --> 00:34:35,035
I'II Iet you get on, Mrs Brimley.

426
00:34:35,520 --> 00:34:39,149
- Good night.
- And don't you worry about Thursday.

427
00:34:39,240 --> 00:34:42,789
I'II feed him his hotpot
and he'II be right as rain.

428
00:34:42,880 --> 00:34:45,633
You just enjoy yourself
with your friend.

429
00:35:14,720 --> 00:35:20,477
But as Thursday evening arrived, i found
my enthusiasm for the event waning.

430
00:35:21,960 --> 00:35:24,952
For in truth the whim that prompted me
to extend the invitation

431
00:35:25,040 --> 00:35:27,031
had lost its piquancy

432
00:35:27,120 --> 00:35:29,793
and the sobering cost of Wrather's Tokay

433
00:35:29,880 --> 00:35:34,715
played its part in making the whole
venture seem somewhat dubious.

434
00:35:38,320 --> 00:35:43,030
I'm afraid I was mistaken about the vintage.
The '89 was unavailable.

435
00:35:43,120 --> 00:35:47,989
This is... this is a '91.
I do hope you're not too disappointed.

436
00:35:48,080 --> 00:35:50,594
Not at all.

437
00:35:50,680 --> 00:35:54,195
One would have to have
a jaded palate indeed

438
00:35:54,280 --> 00:35:58,114
if the prospect
of a '91 KIeverheld-Manschliess

439
00:35:58,200 --> 00:36:00,430
were a disappointment.

440
00:36:03,240 --> 00:36:05,276
Properly decanted.

441
00:36:05,360 --> 00:36:08,238
No sign of sediment.

442
00:36:09,920 --> 00:36:12,150
Well done.

443
00:36:13,280 --> 00:36:14,872
Thank you.

444
00:36:21,840 --> 00:36:26,675
To think that such wine was once
only opened by decree of a Hapsburg

445
00:36:26,760 --> 00:36:29,638
and now,
through the vicissitudes of history,

446
00:36:29,720 --> 00:36:33,429
we Iesser beings
can command such an audience.

447
00:36:36,480 --> 00:36:38,471
Your very good health.

448
00:36:45,400 --> 00:36:49,871
i must confess my first taste of Tokay
was not an illuminating moment.

450
00:36:51,680 --> 00:36:54,274
Rather, my father's dismissal of it
as being too syrupy

451
00:36:54,360 --> 00:36:56,510
seemed remarkably close to the mark.

452
00:36:58,120 --> 00:37:03,433
However, in the dean...
its champion was to hand.

454
00:37:11,720 --> 00:37:14,029
Oh...

455
00:37:24,040 --> 00:37:26,679
Tokay, of course, is unique among wines

456
00:37:26,760 --> 00:37:30,719
in that the aroma
is of more significance than the flavour.

457
00:37:30,800 --> 00:37:36,432
For us humans, alas, that is the pursuit
of the ineffable by the inadequate.

458
00:37:38,880 --> 00:37:41,155
At such moments, one could wish

459
00:37:41,240 --> 00:37:44,471
to possess the olfactory powers
of the canine.

460
00:37:50,440 --> 00:37:54,274
It's often occurred to me
that to pull a dog away from a Iamppost

461
00:37:54,360 --> 00:37:59,150
is akin to seizing a scholar in the
British Museum by the scruff of his neck

462
00:37:59,240 --> 00:38:01,356
and dragging him away from his studies.

464
00:38:04,200 --> 00:38:06,191
Yes.

466
00:38:18,920 --> 00:38:21,275
What are you doing?.

467
00:38:22,600 --> 00:38:25,637
One of those damned motor machines.

468
00:38:25,720 --> 00:38:28,359
Dreadful things, don't you think?.

469
00:38:30,080 --> 00:38:33,755
It must be clear to anyone of perception
that the invention of the internal -

470
00:38:33,840 --> 00:38:36,912
one might even say infernal -
combustion engine

471
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:41,790
will prove to be a complete...
catastrophe for the species.

472
00:38:41,880 --> 00:38:43,313
Quite so.

473
00:38:43,400 --> 00:38:45,436
And have you noticed

474
00:38:45,520 --> 00:38:50,116
that motor cars are exactly the right
height for them to take refuge under?.

475
00:38:51,680 --> 00:38:56,754
Cats. The way they get under motor cars
and can't be got at.

476
00:38:58,200 --> 00:39:00,191
Unless, of course,
you're a very small dog.

477
00:39:02,720 --> 00:39:04,597
I see what you mean.

478
00:39:04,680 --> 00:39:07,592
The trouble with cats is
they have no idea of the rules.

479
00:39:08,880 --> 00:39:12,714
One chases them,
invariably they hide or run up trees.

480
00:39:12,800 --> 00:39:16,634
Or perform that preposterous inflation
they're so fond of,

481
00:39:16,720 --> 00:39:19,280
raising their hair on end.

482
00:39:20,080 --> 00:39:22,116
Well, I was never fooled by that ruse.

483
00:39:23,800 --> 00:39:25,199
No?.

484
00:39:25,280 --> 00:39:27,157
Well, perhaps once or twice
when I was very young,

485
00:39:27,240 --> 00:39:32,268
but once I discovered what devious
and subversive creatures they are...

486
00:39:32,360 --> 00:39:35,830
So you are inclined to agree
with the swami about them.

487
00:39:35,920 --> 00:39:40,152
About cats and how they diminish
man's estimation of himself.

488
00:39:40,240 --> 00:39:41,958
Oh, indeed.

489
00:39:43,840 --> 00:39:48,038
- They have no awe of the masters.
